Question 3: Time Tracking - How Do We Actually Track Active Work Hours?
Current Reality: We have NO mechanism to track active work hours yet.
Challenge:
Ali works 3 days straight (24 hours), then 2-3 weeks off
Can't use Gregorian calendar for "weekly" audits
Need actual hour-based tracking
Proposed Solution:
Implementation: Active Work Hour Tracker
Add to mission-control/state.json:
{
  "mission_control_id": "48707",
  "time_tracking": {
    "total_active_work_hours": 0,
    "last_active_timestamp": null,
    "current_session_start": null,
    "sessions": []
  }
}
Mechanism:
Ali clocks in (starts work session):
./tools/clock-in.sh
Records current_session_start timestamp
Updates SESSION_TIMELINE.md status to AVAILABLE
Ali clocks out (ends work session):
./tools/clock-out.sh
Calculates hours worked: (clock_out_time - current_session_start) / 3600
Adds to total_active_work_hours
Logs session in sessions array
Audit triggers check total_active_work_hours:
Every 24 hours: Librarian routine audit
Every 72 hours: Constitution Keeper review
Triggers are hour-based, not calendar-based
Two-Part Answer:
Part 1 (Immediate): We DON'T have this yet. Options:
Option A: Implement active work hour tracking (requires clock-in/clock-out scripts)
Option B: Use Gregorian calendar as fallback (simpler, less precise)
Option C: Manual tracking (Ali notes "Session 1: 3 hours" in daily log, Librarian updates state.json)
Which do you prefer?
Part 2 (Systemic): If we implement Option A:
Create tools/clock-in.sh and tools/clock-out.sh
Librarian AGENT-00003 maintains time tracking accuracy
All audit schedules reference total_active_work_hours instead of calendar dates
Your call: Automated tracking or Gregorian fallback?
